	<title>0-Dimensional Orientation</title>
	<sub.page.body>
		<block>
			<para>We may regard a point <latex>P</latex> as a copy of <latex>\RNr[0]</latex>. An orientation on <latex>P</latex> has no intuitive content. It is given by formally assigning the value <latex>+1</latex> or <latex>-1</latex> to <latex>P</latex>.</para>
			
			<table align="center" border="3" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="3">
				<row>
					<cell><para><img src="ims/BlueDot.gif"></img></para></cell>
					<cell><para>positive orientation</para></cell>
					<cell><para><latex>\omega(P)=+1</latex></para></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell><para><img src="ims/RedDot.gif"></img></para></cell>
					<cell><para>negative orientation</para></cell>
					<cell><para><latex>\omega(P)=-1</latex></para></cell>
				</row>
			</table>
		</block>
		
		<block>
			<para>While the notion of orientation of a point might seem a bit artificial, it is still quite useful. For example in calculus: pick numbers <latex><![CDATA[ a<b ]]></latex> in <latex>\RNr</latex>, and assign orientations as follows:</para>
			<table align="center" border="3" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="2">
				<row>
					<cell><para>To the interval <latex>[a,b]</latex></para></cell>
					<cell><para>Positive orientation</para></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell><para>To the boundary point <latex>a</latex></para></cell>
					<cell><para>Negative orientation</para></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell><para>To the boundary point <latex>b</latex></para></cell>
					<cell><para>Positive orientation</para></cell>
				</row>
			</table>
			<para>Then the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus for a function <latex>f\from [a,b]\to \RNr</latex> with antiderivative <latex>F</latex> may be formulated as follows</para>
			
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
\aligned
\int_{a}^{b} f(x)\, dx\ &=\ F(b) - F(a) \\
	&=\ \omega(b)F(b) + \omega(a)F(a)
\endaligned
]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>This means that the integral is a quantity which is sensitive to orientation, an observation which is a prerequisite for a full understanding of Stokes Theorem; i.e. the extension of the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus to higher dimensions.</para>
		</block>
	</sub.page.body>
</sub.page>